\section{Related Work}

SFC placement has been widely studied for joint function placement 
and routing. Harutyunyan \textit{et al.} \cite{ilp2022} formulated 
the problem using Mixed Integer Linear Programming (MILP) under 
capacity and delay constraints for 5G networks with latency and 
mobility awareness. Zhang \textit{et al.} \cite{zhang2024sfc_par} 
extended this direction by proposing a robust deployment model for 
parallelized SFCs against traffic uncertainty, formulating the 
problem as a mixed integer second-order cone program with VNF 
sharing to minimize deployment cost. While such optimization-based 
approaches capture structural deployment constraints, they lack 
scalability for dynamic large-scale environments.

With the emergence of edge-cloud deployments, DRL has been explored 
for adaptive SFC placement. Dalgkitsis \textit{et al.} \cite{drl-5g} 
proposed a DDPG-based approach for dynamic VNF placement in 5G 
networks. Building on this, Dalgkitsis \textit{et al.} \cite{schema} 
proposed SCHEMA, a distributed RL algorithm for SFC orchestration 
achieving significant latency reduction. However, these approaches 
assume homogeneous infrastructures, limiting applicability to 
heterogeneous Multi-RAT scenarios.

In 5G environments, Hantouti \textit{et al.} \cite{taleb_sfc_sym} 
proposed a symmetry-aware SFC framework enabling KPI-driven service 
chaining. Farhoudi \textit{et al.} \cite{taleb_drl} explored 
learning-based service composition using deep learning for dynamic 
orchestration in aerial-terrestrial networks. While these works 
incorporate service-level objectives, they do not address 
orchestration under heterogeneous infrastructure conditions with 
jointly enforced QoS constraints.

Graph Neural Networks (GNN) have been increasingly applied to 
resource allocation in communication networks. He \textit{et al.} 
\cite{gnn-v2x} employed GNN with multi-agent RL for spectrum 
allocation in vehicular networks. Bouroudi \textit{et al.} 
\cite{gnn-6g} proposed a GNN-enhanced DRL framework using PPO for 
energy-efficient multi-domain 6G orchestration. While these works 
demonstrate GNN-based DRL effectiveness for resource optimization, 
they do not address SFC placement with globally optimal path 
selection that satisfies end-to-end SLA constraints in heterogeneous 
Multi-RAT environments.

Kubernetes has become the de facto platform for deploying CNFs. 
Arouk and Nikaein \cite{kube5g} proposed Kube5G, a cloud-native 
5G service platform for agile telco network function deployment. 
Han Dong \textit{et al.} \cite{singh2025pax} proposed PAX, a 
performance- and energy-aware scheduler. Tsegaye \textit{et al.} 
\cite{tsegaye2025sdn} proposed a cloud-edge microservices 
architecture integrating SDN, KubeEdge, and Kubernetes DaemonSets 
for real-time medical asset tracking and adaptive telemetry 
enforcement, demonstrating the effectiveness of closed-loop 
edge-AI within Kubernetes environments. The management of SFC 
state consistency during migrations in such programmable 
infrastructures has been experimentally characterized by Yamada 
\textit{et al.} \cite{yamada2025sfc_pdp}, who showed that 
aggregated controller designs can reduce SFC migration time by 76\% 
by eliminating state conversion overhead. Despite these advances, 
existing schedulers remain resource-centric and lack support for 
end-to-end SLA enforcement, energy-aware placement, and SFC-aware 
orchestration.
